    <text>
        <body>
            
            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.26c.61a"/>
                
                <fw type="curatorial">61a</fw>
                
                <opener>
                    <dateline>22 November 1958</dateline>
                
                    <salute>Dear John:</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>My intentions have been good, but my performance dismal. Ever<del>y</del> since we received your gracious note, I've been planning to write and tell you that we enjoyed so much having you with us, and we <del>genuinely</del> hope you'll be able to come back soon and stay longer.</p>
                
                <p>Both Marie and I feel that we were the gainers from your visit, and it's always a pleasure to be near you because you have a capacity <del>that one seldom finds </del> to enrich the lives <add>of</add> all those you come in contact with. And that's something that can be said about few people--all too few.</p>
                
                <p>Right now we're enjoying a visit <del>from our <unclear/></del> by our younger daughter, her husband and baby. Nancy and the baby will be here over Thanksgiving, but her husband has to leave <del>tomorrow night</del> Monday night for Denver and Salt Lake City, to be gone for a week.</p>
                
                <p>Give our best wishes to all your family. I trust that Sig is out of the woods with his difficulties. I'm going to try to get a letter off to Ollie this afternoon, too. I wish <del>yo</del> they would break loose and come here for a weekend visit with us. We miss them so much.</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>Affectionately,</salute>
                    
                    <signed>Ward</signed>
                    <signed>Ward</signed>
                </closer>
                
            </div1>
        </body>
        
